und in many world traditions. Cross-cultural philosophy, comparative theology, and social and cultural psychology all teach that cultures and subcultures vary in how much value they place on life satisfaction or feeling happy. Furthermore, the ideas promoted by the happiness agenda can compete with rights, justice, sustainability, and equality—and even conceal racial and gender injustice.Against Happiness argues that a better way forward requires integration of cross-cultural philosophical, ethical, and political thought with critical social science. Ultimately, the authors contend, happiness should be a secondary goal—worth pursuing only if it is contingent on the demands of justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomicsxPsychological aspects. 0aHappinessxPhilosophy. 0aSocial policyxPsychological aspects. 0aWell-being. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aBingle, Bobby, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFrey, Jennifer A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeDoux, Joseph E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMarkus, Hazel Rose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMesquita, Batja, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMoody-Adams, Michele, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRen, Songyao, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSachs, Jeffrey D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSun, Anna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTsai, Jeanne L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilson, Yolonda Y., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColum